article.description: Second-ranked Duke got off to a slow start but had few problems extending its season-opening winning streak to six games with a 91-57 victory over North Carolina A&T.
article.headline: Coach K: 'No commitment to excellence'
article.linkText: Coach K steamed with Duke's effort in easy win
article.story: GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Mike Krzyzewski has been saying for weeks he wants to see growth from his young team. Duke (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP) didn't show the Hall of Fame coach much progress Tuesday night. Dahntay Jones scored a season-high 18 points and the Blue Devils forced 18 first-half turnovers en route to a 91-57 victory over North Carolina A&T. But Krzyzewski was steamed at his club for what he termed a lackluster effort. "The first half was like a folly of how many ways you could not score inside,'' Krzyzewski said. "It was sad, just sad. It was like we're not doing any drills. "When I retire I'm not going to pull out the tape and show my grandkids. There was no cohesiveness, no energy, no commitment to excellence.'' The Blue Devils, playing for the first time in 10 days, improved to 6-0 for the 12th time in 23 seasons under Krzyzewski. Daniel Ewing added 16 points for Duke. The Blue Devils were 33-for-45 from the free-throw line -- taking 33 more foul shots than the Aggies (0-5), who fell to 0-8 all-time against the Blue Devils. However, Duke shot just 38 percent, had 11 assists and shot 4-for-21 from 3-point range. "I want our team, if we lose or we make mistakes, to have them made out of enthusiastic, aggressive play,'' Krzyzewski said. "That's the atmosphere we try to create for our team. When that's not done, I'm not doing something right because for the 23 years I've been here we've played hard and aggressive and we play to win. There was no spark tonight -- at all.'' Duke's locker room was quiet, and the players were to the point after getting a scolding from Krzyzewski. "There are going to be some changes,'' captain Chris Duhon said. "Expect a lot more intensity -- and heart.'' Duke was rusty at the start, missing 16 of its first 19 shots to fall into a seven-point hole against a team that lost to North Carolina State 101-63 Saturday. But Jones, in a reserve role for the first time this season, sparked his club. He scored seven points in a 70-second span during a 14-1 run as the Blue Devils took control midway through the first half. Duke's spurt reached 27-5 before Jones sank a shot in the lane and a follow over the final 1:21 for a 44-28 lead at halftime. Duke's starters never did find the range in the opening 20 minutes, going a combined 5-for-22 as the Blue Devils shot just 32.6 percent in the half. But Jones was 5-for-10 from the field and 3-for-3 from the line for 13 points in 12 minutes. "He's a tough matchup for most people,'' A&T coach Curtis Hunter said of Jones. "He's strong and athletic. He was the key. When nobody else was doing anything for them he came out and stayed physical and started hitting some shots.'' Krzyzewski didn't start any post players in the second half, searching for some offensive chemistry. It never really came until the final 10 minutes against a program Duke had beaten by an average of 34.4 points. The Aggies, averaging just 53.2 points, never got on track. They scored just 11 points in the opening 11 minutes of the second half as Duke went up 68-39. Steven Koger led North Carolina A&T with 16 points, but the Aggies coughed the ball up 30 times. The game against the Aggies will be Duke's only action in a 22-day span. The Blue Devils will play next on Dec. 29 against Dayton. This was Duke's second game at the Greensboro Coliseum -- the site of this season's Atlantic Coast Conference tournament. The Blue Devils beat Ohio State 91-76 here on Dec. 3.
